# Overview of my contribution:
As a Team Member 1 ,I was responsible to write the parsing module. This module processes raw files of quiz response and obtains the chosen answers in a numerical form of organization. The resultant product is a list of 100 values in which each respondent gave their answers and that is saved in a new text file to be further analyzed.
# How the code works:
The program reads the input files one line at a time and recognizes the beginning of each question with the keyword, Question. It gathers the four potential answer choices to each question and marks the answer choice of the question with the [x] marker. The chosen alternative is transformed into a numerical value (1 to 4) and the questions that have not been answered are treated as 0.
Instead of a for loop, a while loop was employed since the number of lines between questions can be different, and the parsing process can be more flexible and resilient.
# Design decision:
To enhance reliability, error handling was added, like checking the presence of the input file and the presence of 100 valid answers. This makes sure that the information is complete and consistent prior to being transmitted to other modules.
The output is saved to a file per respondent and can thus be easily merged with the work of other team members ( e.g. statistical analysis and visualisation).
# challenges faced:
The primary difficulty was that the format of the input files was to be properly read by the parser because any minor errors in the format might lead to errors. Also, file paths had to be handled with care and the program had to find input files in the right place.
# Limitations and improvements:
The present implementation presupposes a set of four options in each question and a regular structure of the question. The next steps might be to make the parser more adaptable to for matting variations, or to read files directly over the Internet rather than accessing them on disk.
